		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012"></a><br><code>sle2012/paper06</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012</a> paper:</span><br><i>The Program Is the Model: Enabling Transformations@run.time</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/JesúsSánchezCuadrado.html">Jesús Sánchez Cuadrado</a>, <a href="../profile/EstherGuerra.html">Esther Guerra</a>, <a href="../profile/JuandeLara.html">Juan de Lara</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_7">10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_7</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagM">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> The focus is on enabling model-like transformations at runtime, by reflecting programs/APIs into a model representation.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3f.html"><span class="tagL">T3F: API</span></a><ul><li> APIs are treated as the primary “model” abstraction, enabling transformations over program structures exposed via APIs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> The paper operationalizes runtime change via transformation rules that modify program structures through the model view.
</li></ul></li></ul>
